%description:
Regression test for stateful PCEP delegation and PCE-initiated update (RFC 8231 Section
6.1/6.2, Workstream F4 Phase 3, RSVP-MBB mode): a ~RsvpTe ingress delegates a running LSP to
a remote ~Pce (PCRpt), the PCE later recomputes that LSP's path (a ~ScenarioManager
"pce-reoptimize" command -- see ~Pce's own doc comment for why this, not a TED-change-
triggered version, was chosen for testability) and finds a strictly necessary alternate route,
sends a PCUpd, and the PCC applies it via make-before-break using the PCE-supplied ERO
DIRECTLY (no fresh CSPF/PCReq round-trip) -- reusing the exact same ~RsvpTe::createPath()/
createIngressPSB() machinery Workstream C7's own reoptimizeInterval trigger already exercises
(see the sibling rsvpte_mbb.test), just PCE-driven instead of internally triggered.

Same ad hoc diamond + real end-to-end hosts as rsvpte_mbb.test: host1 -- LSR1 -> {LSR2 (600
kbps), LSR3 (10 Mbps)} -> LSR4 -- host4, with LSR1.classifier statically FEC-binding host4's
traffic to lspid 100 (the tunnel's ORIGINAL Lsp_Id) -- unlike rsvpte_mbb.test's own scenario,
LSR2 is never shut down here: both branches are available and healthy for this test's entire
run, and "reoptimizeInterval" is left at its default (0, off), so ~RsvpTe's OWN internal
make-before-break trigger (reactive pathProblem() or periodic reoptimization) never fires --
the ONLY thing that ever reroutes tunnel 1 in this test is the PCE-initiated PCUpd. LSR1 also
runs a ~Pcc (app[0]), LSR4 a ~Pce (app[0]), exactly as in the sibling pcep_pcreq.test (Phase 2)
-- see that test's own addressing/PCEP-startup-lag notes, which apply identically here.

Scenario:
  1. At t=0, tunnel 1 (lspid 100, 50 kbps, permanent, computeEro=true, computationMode="pce",
     delegate=true) is configured from the static traffic.xml. Exactly like pcep_pcreq.test,
     its first createIngressPSB() attempt(s) legitimately fail until the PCEP session comes up
     (~3-5s in, per that test's own TCP-SYN-retransmit-lag note) and the PCRep with a real ERO
     arrives; both branches being equally free, the PCE picks the plain-cheapest LSR2 branch.
     Once the ingress label is installed, ~RsvpTe reports this delegated LSP to the PCE (PCRpt,
     assigning it PLSP-ID 1 -- the first and only delegated LSP in this run).
  2. At t=7s (well after tunnel 1 is fully established and its reservation has flooded to
     LSR4's own TED too -- see pcep_pcreq.test's identical margin/lag rationale for its own
     second tunnel), a scenario add-session brings up tunnel 2 (lspid 200, 520 kbps,
     permanent, an EXPLICIT hardwired route via the LSR2 branch -- deliberately NOT
     computeEro'd/PCE-computed, so it never touches the PCE or ~RsvpTe's own CSPF at all, just
     a plain, independently-signaled admission request). Combined with tunnel 1's own 50 kbps,
     the LSR2 branch now carries 570 of its 600 kbps capacity -- only 30 kbps free, no longer
     enough for a hypothetical 50 kbps request. Critically, tunnel 2's admission succeeding
     does NOT touch tunnel 1's already-established reservation in any way (CAC only ever
     blocks NEW requests, it does not preempt or otherwise disturb an existing one) -- so
     tunnel 1 keeps flowing over the LSR2 branch completely undisturbed by this step, and no
     PathErr/local reroute trigger of any kind fires for it.
  3. At t=9s (2s margin for tunnel 2's reservation to flood to LSR4's TED, mirroring
     pcep_pcreq.test's own convergence-lag lesson), a "pce-reoptimize" ~ScenarioManager
     command names PLSP-ID 1 specifically (NOT "all": tunnel 2's hand-configured route is
     ALSO delegated/reported here, since "delegate" applies at the ~RsvpTe module level to
     every ingress path regardless of whether that particular path's own route came from
     CSPF/the PCE or an explicit XML <route> -- reoptimizing "all" would legitimately also
     migrate tunnel 2 off the now-crowded LSR2 branch, which is real, correct behavior, but
     would only muddy this test's narrower assertions below; the plspid="1" form is exercised
     instead, and is exactly as real a code path as "all"). Re-running CSPF for PLSP-ID 1 with
     its original inputs (50 kbps) now finds the LSR2 branch
     infeasible (only 30 kbps free) and returns the LSR3 branch instead (10 Mbps, ample) --
     a DIFFERENT ERO than the one currently in use, so the PCE sends a PCUpd (srpId=1, the
     first and only one this run). The PCC applies it: ~RsvpTe::applyPceUpdate() signals a
     fresh replacement Lsp_Id (201 -- see maxLspId's own doc comment: it is bumped past every
     XML-configured lspid seen, i.e. past 200, before this event) using the PCE-supplied ERO
     DIRECTLY (verified below by a structural %not-contains: since the ERO handed to
     createIngressPSB() for lspid 201 is already a full strict route, its
     "ERO.empty() || allLoose" CSPF/PCE-delegation guard is never true for it, so neither a
     fresh "PCReq sent to PCE" nor a "PCE computed ERO for session (..., lspid=201)" line is
     ever produced for this specific replacement -- structurally impossible given the code,
     not just something this particular run happens not to trigger). Once lspid 201's ingress
     label is installed, the classifier's FEC entry (originally bound to lspid 100) is rebound
     to it -- the actual traffic cutover -- and lspid 100 is torn down. ~RsvpTe then reports
     PLSP-ID 1's new state to the PCE again (PCRpt, echoing srpId=1, the PCUpd it
     acknowledges).

Asserted:
1. The PCEP session reaches OPERATIONAL, tunnel 1 establishes over the LSR2 branch, and this
   delegated LSP is reported to the PCE (PCRpt) -- all before tunnel 2 ever arrives (ordering
   regex).
2. The PCE's reoptimization actually recomputes PLSP-ID 1 and finds a different (LSR3-branch)
   route, and sends a PCUpd for it; the PCC receives it and applies it via make-before-break,
   ending with the cutover/rebind and a new PCRpt echoing the PCUpd's srpId.
3. No fresh CSPF/PCReq round-trip happened for the replacement lspid (201) -- the PCE-supplied
   ERO was used directly (structural %not-contains, see point 3 in the scenario walkthrough
   above).
4. Traffic keeps flowing end to end, strongly (not just nonzero), across the whole run
   including the cutover (packetReceived:count postrun-scalar check, same idiom as
   rsvpte_mbb.test/ldp_ipv6_fec.test).
5. Standard undisposed-object postrun guard.

%#--------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------
%file: PcepPcupdDiamond.ned

import inet.common.scenario.ScenarioManager;
import inet.node.mpls.RsvpMplsRouter;
import inet.node.inet.StandardHost;

//
// Ad hoc diamond, with real end-to-end hosts: host1 -- LSR1 -> {LSR2 (600 kbps), LSR3 (10
// Mbps)} -> LSR4 -- host4. Identical shape/metrics/bandwidths to rsvpte_mbb.test's
// RsvpteMbbDiamond; LSR1/LSR4 additionally run a PCEP Pcc/Pce pair as app[0] (see test.ini),
// exactly like pcep_pcreq.test's own PcepCspfDiamond.
//
network PcepPcupdDiamond
{
    parameters:
        **.ipv4.configurator.networkConfiguratorModule = "";
    submodules:
        host1: StandardHost {
            @display("p=50,200");
            gates: pppg[1];
        }
        host4: StandardHost {
            @display("p=650,200");
            gates: pppg[1];
        }
        LSR1: RsvpMplsRouter {
            @display("p=200,200");
            gates: pppg[3];
        }
        LSR2: RsvpMplsRouter {
            @display("p=400,100");
            gates: pppg[2];
        }
        LSR3: RsvpMplsRouter {
            @display("p=400,300");
            gates: pppg[2];
        }
        LSR4: RsvpMplsRouter {
            @display("p=600,200");
            gates: pppg[3];
        }
        scenarioManager: ScenarioManager {
            @display("p=100,100;is=s");
        }
    connections:
        host1.pppg[0] <--> { delay = 1ms; datarate = 10Mbps; } <--> LSR1.pppg[0];
        LSR1.pppg[1] <--> { delay = 1ms; datarate = 600kbps; } <--> LSR2.pppg[0];
        LSR2.pppg[1] <--> { delay = 1ms; datarate = 600kbps; } <--> LSR4.pppg[0];
        LSR1.pppg[2] <--> { delay = 1ms; datarate = 10Mbps; } <--> LSR3.pppg[0];
        LSR3.pppg[1] <--> { delay = 1ms; datarate = 10Mbps; } <--> LSR4.pppg[1];
        LSR4.pppg[2] <--> { delay = 1ms; datarate = 10Mbps; } <--> host4.pppg[0];
}

%#--------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------
%# Addressing (identical to rsvpte_mbb.test): host1.ppp0=10.0.0.1 <-> LSR1.ppp0=10.0.0.2
%#             LSR1.ppp1=10.0.1.1 <-> LSR2.ppp0=10.0.1.2 (600k branch, hop A, metric 1)
%#             LSR2.ppp1=10.0.2.1 <-> LSR4.ppp0=10.0.2.2 (600k branch, hop B, metric 1)
%#             LSR1.ppp2=10.0.3.1 <-> LSR3.ppp0=10.0.3.2 (10M branch, hop A, metric 5)
%#             LSR3.ppp1=10.0.4.1 <-> LSR4.ppp1=10.0.4.2 (10M branch, hop B, metric 5)
%#             LSR4.ppp2=10.0.5.1 <-> host4.ppp0=10.0.5.2
%# routerId="auto" picks the HIGHEST interface address per LSR:
%#   LSR1 = max(10.0.0.2, 10.0.1.1, 10.0.3.1) = 10.0.3.1
%#   LSR2 = max(10.0.1.2, 10.0.2.1) = 10.0.2.1
%#   LSR3 = max(10.0.3.2, 10.0.4.1) = 10.0.4.1
%#   LSR4 = max(10.0.2.2, 10.0.4.2, 10.0.5.1) = 10.0.5.1
%# The PCEP session connects LSR1's Pcc to LSR4's routerId (10.0.5.1), over the genuinely
%# multi-hop route ~LinkStateRouting installs -- same rationale as pcep_pcreq.test.
%file: LSR1.rt
ifconfig:
name: ppp0	inet_addr: 10.0.0.2	MULTICAST	MTU: 1500	Groups: 224.0.0.0	Metric: 1
name: ppp1	inet_addr: 10.0.1.1	MULTICAST	MTU: 1500	Groups: 224.0.0.0	Metric: 1
name: ppp2	inet_addr: 10.0.3.1	MULTICAST	MTU: 1500	Groups: 224.0.0.0	Metric: 5
ifconfigend.

route:
224.0.0.0	*	255.0.0.0	H	0	ppp0
224.0.0.0	*	255.0.0.0	H	0	ppp1
224.0.0.0	*	255.0.0.0	H	0	ppp2
routeend.

%#--------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------
%file: LSR2.rt
ifconfig:
name: ppp0	inet_addr: 10.0.1.2	MULTICAST	MTU: 1500	Groups: 224.0.0.0	Metric: 1
name: ppp1	inet_addr: 10.0.2.1	MULTICAST	MTU: 1500	Groups: 224.0.0.0	Metric: 1
ifconfigend.

route:
224.0.0.0	*	255.0.0.0	H	0	ppp0
224.0.0.0	*	255.0.0.0	H	0	ppp1
routeend.

%#--------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------
%file: LSR3.rt
ifconfig:
name: ppp0	inet_addr: 10.0.3.2	MULTICAST	MTU: 1500	Groups: 224.0.0.0	Metric: 5
name: ppp1	inet_addr: 10.0.4.1	MULTICAST	MTU: 1500	Groups: 224.0.0.0	Metric: 5
ifconfigend.

route:
224.0.0.0	*	255.0.0.0	H	0	ppp0
224.0.0.0	*	255.0.0.0	H	0	ppp1
routeend.

%#--------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------
%file: LSR4.rt
ifconfig:
name: ppp0	inet_addr: 10.0.2.2	MULTICAST	MTU: 1500	Groups: 224.0.0.0	Metric: 1
name: ppp1	inet_addr: 10.0.4.2	MULTICAST	MTU: 1500	Groups: 224.0.0.0	Metric: 5
name: ppp2	inet_addr: 10.0.5.1	MULTICAST	MTU: 1500	Groups: 224.0.0.0	Metric: 1
ifconfigend.

route:
224.0.0.0	*	255.0.0.0	H	0	ppp0
224.0.0.0	*	255.0.0.0	H	0	ppp1
224.0.0.0	*	255.0.0.0	H	0	ppp2
routeend.

%#--------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------
%file: host1.rt
ifconfig:
name: ppp0	inet_addr: 10.0.0.1	MTU: 1500	Metric: 1
ifconfigend.

route:
10.0.0.2	*		255.255.255.255	H	0	ppp0
default:	10.0.0.2	0.0.0.0		G	0	ppp0
routeend.

%#--------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------
%file: host4.rt
ifconfig:
name: ppp0	inet_addr: 10.0.5.2	MTU: 1500	Metric: 1
ifconfigend.

route:
10.0.5.1	*		255.255.255.255	H	0	ppp0
default:	10.0.5.1	0.0.0.0		G	0	ppp0
routeend.

%#--------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------
%# fecid 1 is statically bound to lspid 100 (tunnel 1's ORIGINAL Lsp_Id); the whole point of
%# this test is that the PCUpd-driven make-before-break cutover rebinds it to the fresh
%# replacement Lsp_Id (201) itself -- nothing here ever references 201 directly.
%file: LSR1_fec.xml
<?xml version="1.0"?>
<fectable>
	<fecentry>
		<id>1</id>
		<destination>10.0.5.2</destination>
		<tunnel_id>1</tunnel_id>
		<endpoint>LSR4%routerId</endpoint>
		<lspid>100</lspid>
	</fecentry>
</fectable>

%#--------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------
%file: LSR1_rsvp.xml
<?xml version="1.0"?>
<sessions>
	<session>
		<endpoint>LSR4%routerId</endpoint>
		<tunnel_id>1</tunnel_id>

		<paths>
			<path>
				<lspid>100</lspid>
				<bandwidth>50000</bandwidth>
				<permanent>true</permanent>
			</path>
		</paths>
	</session>
</sessions>

%#--------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------
%file: scenario.xml
<?xml version="1.0"?>
<scenario>
	<at t="7s">
		<add-session module="LSR1.rsvp">
			<endpoint>LSR4%routerId</endpoint>
			<tunnel_id>2</tunnel_id>

			<paths>
				<path>
					<lspid>200</lspid>
					<bandwidth>520000</bandwidth>
					<permanent>true</permanent>
					<route>
						<node>LSR2%routerId</node>
						<node>LSR4%routerId</node>
					</route>
				</path>
			</paths>
		</add-session>
	</at>
	<at t="9s">
		<pce-reoptimize module="LSR4.app[0]" plspid="1"/>
	</at>
</scenario>

%#--------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------
%inifile: test.ini

[General]
ned-path = .;../../../../src
network = PcepPcupdDiamond
sim-time-limit = 14s
total-stack = 64MiB
record-vector-results = false
cmdenv-express-mode = false
%# rsvp modules at detail (to capture the CSPF/label-install/reporting EV_DETAIL lines) and
%# the classifier + PCEP apps at info; everything else off, same rationale/convention as
%# rsvpte_mbb.test/pcep_pcreq.test. Per-module cmdenv-log-level overrides are matched in FILE
%# ORDER (first matching pattern wins), so specific overrides MUST be declared before the
%# general catch-all below.
**.LSR1.rsvp.cmdenv-log-level = detail
**.LSR4.rsvp.cmdenv-log-level = detail
**.LSR1.classifier.cmdenv-log-level = info
**.LSR1.app[0].cmdenv-log-level = info
**.LSR4.app[0].cmdenv-log-level = info
**.cmdenv-log-level = off

**.host1.numApps = 1
**.host1.app[0].typename = "UdpBasicApp"
**.host1.app[0].localPort = 100
**.host1.app[0].destPort = 100
**.host1.app[0].messageLength = 128 bytes
**.host1.app[0].sendInterval = 0.02s
**.host1.app[0].destAddresses = "10.0.5.2"

**.host4.numApps = 1
**.host4.app[0].typename = "UdpSink"
**.host4.app[0].localPort = 100

**.host1.ipv4.routingTable.routingFile = "host1.rt"
**.host4.ipv4.routingTable.routingFile = "host4.rt"
**.LSR1.ipv4.routingTable.routingFile = "LSR1.rt"
**.LSR2.ipv4.routingTable.routingFile = "LSR2.rt"
**.LSR3.ipv4.routingTable.routingFile = "LSR3.rt"
**.LSR4.ipv4.routingTable.routingFile = "LSR4.rt"

**.LSR1.classifier.config = xmldoc("LSR1_fec.xml")
**.LSR1.rsvp.traffic = xmldoc("LSR1_rsvp.xml")

**.LSR1.rsvp.computeEro = true
**.LSR1.rsvp.computationMode = "pce"
**.LSR1.rsvp.pccModule = "^.app[0]"
**.LSR1.rsvp.delegate = true

**.LSR*.rsvp.helloInterval = 0.2s
**.LSR*.rsvp.helloTimeout = 0.5s

%# PCEP: LSR1 (ingress) runs the Pcc, LSR4 (two hops away, genuinely remote) runs the Pce,
%# wired to LSR4's own (fully converged) Ted -- exactly as in pcep_pcreq.test.
**.LSR1.hasTcp = true
**.LSR1.numApps = 1
**.LSR1.app[0].typename = "Pcc"
**.LSR1.app[0].pceAddress = "10.0.5.1"
**.LSR1.app[0].localAddress = "10.0.3.1"
**.LSR1.app[0].rsvpteModule = "^.rsvp"
**.LSR1.app[0].keepaliveTime = 2s
**.LSR1.app[0].deadTimer = 10s
**.LSR1.app[0].reconnectInterval = 1s

**.LSR4.hasTcp = true
**.LSR4.numApps = 1
**.LSR4.app[0].typename = "Pce"
**.LSR4.app[0].tedModule = "^.ted"
**.LSR4.app[0].keepaliveTime = 2s
**.LSR4.app[0].deadTimer = 10s

**.ppp[*].queue.typename = "DropTailQueue"
**.ppp[*].queue.packetCapacity = 10

*.*.hasStatus = true
**.scenarioManager.script = xmldoc("scenario.xml")

%#--------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------
%# Assertion 1: PCEP session up, tunnel 1 established over the LSR2 branch (matching
%# rsvpte_cspf.test-style CSPF results on the identical topology's metrics), and this
%# delegated LSP reported to the PCE -- all before tunnel 2 (added at t=7s) ever shows up in
%# the traffic database (ordering regex; %contains-regex matches with re.DOTALL, so a lone
%# ".*" filler line can absorb any number of intervening lines, same convention as
%# pcep_pcreq.test's own ordering regex).
%contains-regex: stdout
PCEP session with .* is now OPERATIONAL
.*
PCE computed ERO for session \(dest=10.0.5.1, lspid=100\): 10.0.2.1, 10.0.5.1
.*
reporting delegated LSP UP to PCE \(plspId=1, lspid=100, ERO 10.0.2.1, 10.0.5.1\)
PCRpt sent to PCE \(plspId=1, srpId=0, up=1, ERO with 2 hop\(s\)\)
.*
adding new session into database
%#--------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------
%# Assertion 2: the PCE receives and remembers the PCRpt.
%contains-regex: stdout
PCRpt received from .* \(plspId=1, srpId=0, delegate=1, up=1, ERO with 2 hop\(s\)\)
%#--------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------
%# Assertion 2 (continued): the pce-reoptimize command (t=9s) recomputes PLSP-ID 1, finds the
%# LSR2 branch no longer feasible (30 kbps free < the 50 kbps tunnel 1 needs, after tunnel 2's
%# 520 kbps admission alongside tunnel 1's own 50 kbps) and the LSR3 branch instead, and sends
%# a PCUpd for it.
%contains: stdout
pce-reoptimize: found a better path for PLSP-ID 1 (10.0.4.1, 10.0.5.1), sending PCUpd
%#--------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------
%contains: stdout
PCUpd sent to 10.0.3.1 (srpId=1, plspId=1, ERO with 2 hop(s))
%#--------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------
%contains: stdout
PCUpd received from PCE (srpId=1, plspId=1, ERO with 2 hop(s))
%#--------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------
%# The PCC applies it: a fresh replacement Lsp_Id (201) signaled via make-before-break, using
%# the PCE-supplied ERO directly.
%contains: stdout
PCUpd received for PLSP-ID 1: re-routing lspid=100 via make-before-break with the PCE-supplied ERO (10.0.4.1, 10.0.5.1)
%#--------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------
%# Cutover completes (lspid 201 up, classifier rebound from lspid 100, lspid 100 torn down) --
%# ordering regex, same crux-assertion shape as rsvpte_mbb.test's own MBB cutover check.
%contains-regex: stdout
installing label for 201 outLabel=.*
make-before-break cutover: lspid=201 is up, switching traffic away from lspid=100.*
make-before-break cutover: rebinding fec id 1 from lspid 100 to lspid 201.*
sending PathTear to .*
%#--------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------
%# The cutover is reported back to the PCE, echoing the PCUpd's own srpId (1) -- RFC 8231
%# Section 7.2's correlator round trip.
%contains: stdout
reporting delegated LSP UP to PCE (plspId=1, lspid=201, ERO 10.0.4.1, 10.0.5.1)
%#--------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------
%contains: stdout
PCRpt sent to PCE (plspId=1, srpId=1, up=1, ERO with 2 hop(s))
%#--------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------
%# Assertion 3: no fresh CSPF/PCReq round-trip happened for the replacement lspid (201) -- the
%# PCE-supplied ERO was used directly (see the scenario walkthrough's point 3 above for why
%# this is structurally guaranteed, not incidental).
%not-contains: stdout
PCE computed ERO for session (dest=10.0.5.1, lspid=201)
%#--------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------
%# Assertion 4: strong (not just nonzero) end-to-end delivery across the whole run, including
%# the cutover -- same postrun-scalar idiom as rsvpte_mbb.test.
%postrun-command: grep "packetReceived:count" results/General-#0.sca | awk '$NF > 500 { print "DELIVERED", $0 }' > delivered.out
%contains: delivered.out
DELIVERED
%#--------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------
%postrun-command: grep "undisposed object:" test.out > test_undisposed.out || true
%not-contains: test_undisposed.out
undisposed object: (
%#--------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------
